Citizens demanding the dismantling of the Special Anti-Robbery Squad, has accuses of human rights violations, have taken their protest to Louis Edet House, the police force headquarters in Abuja. The protest on Thursday was one of several taking place at different locations including at the Lagos House of Assembly and Lekki Toll Gate, both in Lagos. The protest at the Lekki toll was forcefully broken up by police who arrived on the scene not long after it started. Some celebrities including Falz and Naira Marley were part of organizing the Lekki protest. The EndSARS protesters in Abuja held placards calling for the end of the unit, close to the police headquarters and shooting EndSARS. Publisher of Sahara Reporters, Omoleye Sowore,  led the protesters who partly disrupted the flow of traffic on Shehu Shagari way. They also poured red paint on the road to demonstrate the extrajudicial killings of Nigerians that that been blamed on members of the police unit, SARS. President Muhammadu Buhari has called for the quick passage of the 2021 budget by the National Assembly. Speaking on Thursday while presenting the N13trn budget proposal to the lawmekers, Buhari said passing it on time will ensure early implementation from January 2021. As part of measures to contain the COVID-19 outbreak, the president was accompanied to the National Assembly by only the vice president, Yemi Osinbajo and a handful of ministers. In his presentation, the president said the allocation to education had been increased by 65 percent while the Second Niger Bridge has reached 46 percent completion. Personnel cost, he was remained the single largest item on the expenditure list, expressing determination to totally eliminate ghost workers. Some of the major highlights in the budget include a N128bn allocation made to the National Assembly. The president also directed that there be more vigilant monitoring of revenue generating agencies of government.